data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11 (.NET 11), the Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. The workaround you had in .NET 10 (e.g., configuring `CosmosOptionsExtension` to allow synchronous I/O) no longer exists. All synchronous LINQ operators — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

The Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async; EF Core previously shimmed sync calls on your behalf, but that shim is now gone.

## How to fix it

Convert every synchronous call to its `async` counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return types become `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void)
2. `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
3. `await` each call; mark methods `async`
4. Callers up the chain must also become async (`async` all the way up)

> **Tip:** `Add()` stays synchronous — it's an in-memory tracking call, not a database operation. Only the query/save operations need the async switch.
